      "id": "79782cca_25d263a4",
      "file_path": "PolicyEngineUtils/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/utils/PeCryptoUtils.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 48,
      "message": "adding \"synchronized\" here just prevents two threads from invoking initAesKey() at the same time; it does not prevent one thread from changing the key while another decrypts().  Seems like the whole problem would be solved by changing the \"static\" methods to regular methods, and passing the AES key to the constructor.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 811,
        "name": "Jim Hahn",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "jrh3@att.com",
        "username": "jrh3"
      },
      "updated": "2019-03-26 20:22:49.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": null,
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "1794fd0b_f1df03d6",
      "file_path": "PolicyEngineUtils/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/utils/PeCryptoUtils.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 48,
      "message": "Maybe im missing something but the key is only used to init CryptoUtils once. A change to key later will not reinit CryptoUtils. Assumption is one key per app. If different keys are needed later, we can instantiate CryptoUtils directly.\nIf the apps were modified to decrypt all the reqd passwords once at init and make it accessible throughout the app, there would be no need for this class and caching.",
      "author": {
        "account_id": 2757,
        "name": "Praveen Augustus",
        "display_name": null,
        "email": "pa834y@att.com",
        "username": "pa834y"
      },
      "updated": "2019-03-26 21:59:21.000000000",
      "in_reply_to": "79782cca_25d263a4",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "id": "dd05b7d4_130b9290",
      "file_path": "PolicyEngineUtils/src/main/java/org/onap/policy/utils/PeCryptoUtils.java",
      "patchset_number": 2,
      "line": 48,
      "message": "That's what I thought, but then I saw a number of places where the code does init & decrypt, so left me skeptical.  (In addition, I tend to dislike static methods, as a general rule, because they're generally not object-oriented.)",
